<TITLE> CID starts quizzing ex-home secy in Ctg arms case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, Oct 3 (bdnews24.com)The Criminal Investigation Department of police have started interrogating former home secretary Omar Faruque in connection with the 2004 seizure of 10 truckloads of arms in the port city, an official said on Saturday. Mohammad Muslim, special superintendent of Chittagong division of CID, told bdnews24.com the questioning began around 11am at the Damparha office of CID. On receiving a summons, Faruque reported to the CID office where a team headed by investigation officer Moniruzzaman Chowdhury started to quiz him. Faruque had led a five-member official investigation team to probe the notorious arms case in which police seized 10 trucks of weapons and ammunition on April 1, 2004 when the consignment was being offloaded at the jetty of Chittagong Urea Fertiliser Ltd, Muslim said. He said that Faruque was being interrogated to expedite the investigation as he was the home secretary at that time and also led the official team to probe the incident. But he declined to elaborate on what Faruque was being questioned about. CID have questioned persons involved in the arms offloading and using of the jetty and so far interrogated CUFL officials, coastguards, truck owners, police and officers of the National Security Intelligence agency after the new IO, Moniruzzaman, took charge of the investigation. So far seven people have been arrestedfive officers of NSI including two of its former chiefsand former managing director and general manager (administration) of CUFL. The IO is now interrogating some 23 people who have been on bail in this case. Two cases had been filed on illegal arms trafficking and smuggling one day after the seizure of the cache by the officer-in-charge of Karnaphuli Police Station, Ahadur Rahman. CID submitted two charge sheets on 43 in the illegal arms case and 44 in the smuggling case after investigation. bd
